{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503035"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1927"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1927"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.22,0.71,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98053"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1927"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80572"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"120"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8726"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98053"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 54-year-old man presents with a six-month history of a painless swelling in the right side of his scrotum. It does not change in size, no matter if he is sitting, standing or coughing. He has no history of trauma or other symptoms, and his medical history is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the scrotum appears abnormal (Image). The mass is non-tender, fluctuant, and transilluminates. The top of the mass is palpable and appears to be separate from the testis. Both testes are palpable and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inguino-scrotal hernia","Varicocele","Epididymal cyst","Testicular tumour","Ectopic testis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpididymal cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are fluid-filled epididymal collections that most often occur in middle-aged to elderly men. They are soft, fluctuant, and may be tender on palpation, though often painless. As they are fluid-filled, they will transilluminate and appear as a well-defined anechoic lesion on trans-scrotal ultrasound. They are characteristically superior and posterior to the testis, differentiating it from a hydrocoele which surrounds the testis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn\u003Cstrong\u003E inguino-scrotal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E will often enlarge in size when coughing or standing, due to an increase in intra-abdominal pressure. The top of the lump will not be palpable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricoceles\u003C/strong\u003E will be compressible and may flatten or collapse when the patient is supine, and have a \u0027bag of worms\u0027 appearance due to the engorgement of the venous pampiniform plexus. They can enlarge with increased intra-abdominal pressure/Valsalva manoeuvres. This is not observed in the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etesticular tumour\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely given the history of the patient, absence of risk factors (e.g. cryptorchidism, family history), the fluctuance and transillumination of the mass, and its separation from the testis. It is most common in men aged 15-45 years old. However, a trans-scrotal ultrasound should still be used to exclude malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eectopic (or undescended) testis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to present with a scrotal lump at his age, and both of the patient\u0027s testes are palpable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epididymal cysts are painless, fluctuant, and transilluminant masses superior to the testis.","Scrotal lumps that change in size with coughing or lying down are suspicious of an inguino-scrotal hernia or varicocele.","Trans-scrotal ultrasound is the first-line investigation for scrotal lumps."],"references":["Farne H, Norris E C, and Warbrick J S, \u0027Scrotal mass\u0027,  Oxford Cases in Medicine and Surgery [Internet]. New York: Oxford Academic; 2015 [Accessed 2023 Jan 23]. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1093/oso/9780198716228.003.0031.","Gaddam SJ, Chesnut GT. Testicle Cancer. StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 [Accessed 2023 Jan 23]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563159/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80572"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1927"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18939"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18939"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a5e9ab44-275e-4527-ba11-ff94d2d9d57c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a5e9ab44-275e-4527-ba11-ff94d2d9d57c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80572"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-10T19:40:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-10T19:40:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1927"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98053"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{